    {
    (x  = (x + x));
    }

  }

{;//@ assert( (x >= 1) );
}
}
```

1. Make a note of the pre-conditions or variable assignments in the program.
   - x is initialized to 1.
   - y, z1, z2, and z3 are uninitialized (garbage values).

2. Analyze the loop body and make a note of the loop condition.
   - Loop condition: x < y
   - Loop body: x = x + x (doubling the value of x in each iteration)

3. Output loop invariants that are true 
   (i) before the loop execution, 
   (ii) in every iteration of the loop and 
   (iii) after the loop termination, 
   such that the loop invariants imply the post condition.

```c
/*@ 
    loop invariant x >= 1;
    loop invariant x <= y || x == 1;
*/
```

These loop invariants ensure that:
- x is always greater than or equal to 1 throughout the loop execution.
- x is either less than or equal to y or x is equal to 1. This ensures that the loop terminates when x becomes greater than y, and the post-condition x >= 1 is satisfied.

